This paper is about the implementation of a driver for pattern formation and self-organization in collective robot systems. The focus is on the evolution of complex robot behaviors, which is a core topic in robotics (cs.RO). The paper also discusses the use of fitness functions to bias the evolution of behaviors, which is a common approach in machine learning (cs.MA). The paper also mentions the use of prediction networks and action-selection networks, which are common in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the paper discusses the use of emergent patterns and minimal surprise, which are concepts from neural networks and information theory (cs.NE).
